"Kuzyk Z.Z.A., MacDonald R.W., Johannessen S.C., Stern G.A.","Biogeochemical controls on PCB deposition in Hudson Bay",2010,"Environmental Science and Technology","44","9",,"3280","3285",,,10.1021/es903832t,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77951824800&partnerID=40&md5=33f150708c85e43410ca56c6234ec67b","Centre for Earth Observation Science, Department of Environment and Geography, University of Manitoba, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N2, Canada; Freshwater Institute, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 501 University Crescent, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N6, Canada; Institute of Ocean Sciences, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 9860 West Saanich Road, Sidney, BC, V8L 4B2, Canada; INRS-ETE, Université du Quebec, 490 rue de la Couronne, Quebec, QC G1K 9A9, Canada","Kuzyk, Z.Z.A., Centre for Earth Observation Science, Department of Environment and Geography, University of Manitoba, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N2, Canada, Freshwater Institute, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 501 University Crescent, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N6, Canada, INRS-ETE, Université du Quebec, 490 rue de la Couronne, Quebec, QC G1K 9A9, Canada; MacDonald, R.W., Centre for Earth Observation Science, Department of Environment and Geography, University of Manitoba, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N2, Canada, Institute of Ocean Sciences, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 9860 West Saanich Road, Sidney, BC, V8L 4B2, Canada; Johannessen, S.C., Institute of Ocean Sciences, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 9860 West Saanich Road, Sidney, BC, V8L 4B2, Canada; Stern, G.A., Centre for Earth Observation Science, Department of Environment and Geography, University of Manitoba, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N2, Canada, Freshwater Institute, Fisheries and Oceans Canada, 501 University Crescent, Winnipeg, MB, R3T 2N6, Canada","PCB concentrations, congener patterns, and fluxes were examined in 13 dated and organically characterized (C, N, δ13C, δ15N) marine sediment cores from Hudson Bay, Canada, to investigate the importance of organic matter (OM) supply and transport to PCB sequestration. Drawdown of PCBs, supported by marine primary production, is reflected in elevated -PCB concentrations and more highly chlorinated PCB signatures in surface sediments underlying eutrophic regions. Sediments in oligotrophic regions, which are dominated by ""old"" marine OM, have lower PCB concentrations and weathered signatures. For the surface of Hudson Bay, average atmospheric deposition appears to be very low (ca. 1.4 pg -PCBs cm-2 a-1) compared to fluxes reported for nearby lakes (ca. 44 pg -PCBs cm-2 a-1). 210Pb fails to provide a means to normalize the fluxes, highlighting important differences in the biocycling of 210Pb and PCBs. Unlike 210Pb, atmospheric PCB exchange with the waters surface is partially forced by the aquatic organic carbon cycle. The extremely low atmospheric deposition of PCBs to the surface of Hudson Bay is likely a reflection of the Bays exceptionally low productivity and vertical carbon fluxes. If future marine production and vertical flux of carbon increase due to loss of ice cover or change in river input as consequences of global warming, PCB deposition would also increase. © 2010 American Chemical Society.",,"Atmospheric depositions; Atmospheric PCB; Biogeochemical controls; Carbon fluxes; Congener pattern; Hudson Bay; Ice cover; Marine sediments; Oligotrophic regions; Organic carbon cycle; Organic matter; PCB concentration; Primary production; River input; Surface sediments; Vertical fluxes; Atmospheric chemistry; Biogeochemistry; Global warming; Lead; Meteorological problems; Organic carbon; Sedimentology; Sediments; Submarine geology; Polychlorinated biphenyls; carbon; lead 210; organic matter; polychlorinated biphenyl; biogeochemistry; carbon flux; global warming; ice cover; marine sediment; oligotrophic environment; organic matter; PCB; primary production; sediment core; waste disposal; article; biogeochemistry; Canada; greenhouse effect; water analysis; Air; Atmosphere; Canada; Chlorine; Environmental Monitoring; 